> Currently tomato uses SDL3, which is known not to work on powerpc, but I might be able to be convinced to refactor the code and make the SDL code plug-able and eg. be replaced with SDL2. Assuming you can compile c++17...

@Green-Sky If SDL3 can still use X11, then it can probably work (Cocoa is broken ages ago anyway, so chance of fixing it even in SDL2), if X11 support is dropped, then that may be a trouble. (Wayland builds but probably broken, untested at best.)

C++17 is not an issue. With minor reservations C++23 is supported, since we have the latest gcc working.

> We're actually now on Qt6.

@iphydf Somewhat on a side note, in a way I think there are higher chances to get Qt6 fixed rather than Qt5 for powerpc (because at least it moved to CMake, so hacking through the build system itself does not take insane effort), however we need X11 backend to work, and that presently is broken on _any_ macOS. Last time I gave it a go, I could fix qtbase with X11 on Sonoma (just the build, no idea how much more will be needed to get it to work properly), but powerpc build got stuck on an obscure error with stuff pulled in from Apple headers, and I left it there. It is probably fixable with a reasonable effort, but qtbase is not sufficient pretty much for anything, and stuff like qtwebengine will never be fixed (broken even on OpenBSD ppc, AFAIK, and there are more people doing something there than on Darwin).
Qt4 is probably sufficient for every need besides modern web-browsing, but I can imagine that it is non-trivial to maintain compatibility with it: Qt upstream did everything to make it painful LOL
